---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Mosfet from '../components/Mosfet.svelte';
import Voltage from '../components/Voltage.astro';
import LogicGate from '../components/LogicGate.svelte';
import Bits from '../components/Bits.svelte';
import CallStack from '../components/CallStack.svelte';
import Scheduler from '../components/Scheduler.svelte';
import Tracer from '../components/Tracer.svelte';
import Transistor from '../components/Transistor.astro';
import Adder from '../components/Adder.svelte';
import NumbersThings from '../components/NumbersThings.svelte';
import RuntimePipeline from '../components/RuntimePipeline.astro';
import Cpu from '../components/Cpu.svelte';
import MemoryHierarchy from '../components/MemoryHierarchy.astro';
import DataStructures from '../components/DataStructures.astro';
import Encapsulation from '../components/Encapsulation.svelte';
import Packets from '../components/Packets.svelte';
import Cloud from '../components/Cloud.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
---
<Base>
  <section class="layer zone-physical" id="Lsi" data-title="Silicon">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">−01</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Before the switch: a rock we taught to decide</h2><div class="sub">physical · semiconductors · the MOSFET</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Silicon becomes useful when tiny impurities let a gate voltage open or close a path for electrons.</p>
    <Mosfet client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A MOSFET is the physical trick that turns material into a controllable switch.</Takeaway>
    <p class="aside">Past the threshold, the gate pulls a <span class="hl">channel</span> into existence: current flows.</p>
    <Why
      problem="Raw silicon is only a material. To build a computer, we need matter that can be pushed between two dependable behaviors: blocking current or letting it pass."
      idea="Doping changes the material so a gate voltage can pull a temporary channel into place. That turns a tiny patch of silicon into a controllable switch."
      tradeoff="Because the switch is physical, it has limits: heat, leakage, manufacturing variation, and the fact that smaller parts are harder to control."
      next="Once matter can switch reliably, electricity can carry a clean state instead of just being messy motion."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-physical" id="L0" data-title="Voltage">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">00</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>A wire that is either pushed or not</h2><div class="sub">physical · electricity</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">At the bottom there are no zeros and ones — just <b>voltage</b> read as <span class="hl">HIGH</span> or <span class="hl">LOW</span>.</p>
    <Voltage />
    <Takeaway>Voltage is the physical alphabet: LOW and HIGH are the first two symbols.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A computer needs a physical signal it can sample again and again without asking a human what it means."
      idea="Treat voltage as a range, not a perfect value: low enough means LOW, high enough means HIGH. The exact number can wobble while the meaning stays stable."
      tradeoff="Noise, delay, and weak signals can land in the unsafe middle. Good digital circuits leave enough margin that most wobble is ignored."
      next="A transistor uses one voltage state to control another, turning representation into action."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-physical" id="L1" data-title="Transistor">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">01</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The transistor: a wire that controls another wire</h2><div class="sub">physical · the switch</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">A transistor is a switch with no moving parts: one voltage controls whether another can flow.</p>
    <Transistor />
    <Takeaway>A transistor lets one signal decide whether another signal can pass.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Voltage can say HIGH or LOW, but a computer also needs one signal to influence another signal."
      idea="A transistor is the basic if-statement of hardware: if the gate is active, current can pass; otherwise the path stays closed."
      tradeoff="One transistor is easy to understand. Billions together create hard engineering problems around timing, power, heat, and layout."
      next="When transistors are wired in patterns, they become gates that compute true and false."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-physical" id="L2" data-title="Logic gates">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">02</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Gates: transistors that compute true & false</h2><div class="sub">logic · boolean algebra</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Wire switches into patterns and electricity starts making <b>decisions</b>.</p>
    <LogicGate client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Logic gates are decisions made out of transistor patterns.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Individual switches can control current, but computation needs dependable rules: given these inputs, always produce that output."
      idea="Logic gates package transistor patterns into reusable decisions like AND, OR, NOT, and XOR. They let circuits answer small questions mechanically."
      tradeoff="Every gate takes time and consumes power. Large circuits must coordinate thousands of tiny delays so the answer arrives when expected."
      next="Multiple true/false answers side by side can be treated as a binary number."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-number" id="L3" data-title="Bits → numbers">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">03</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Eight wires become a number</h2><div class="sub">numbers · binary place value</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Line up on/off wires, give each one a place value, and the pattern <b>is a number</b>.</p>
    <Bits client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Binary is not magic; it is place value applied to on/off wires.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Yes/no is enough for decisions, but programs need quantities: how many, which address, what color, which character."
      idea="Binary place value gives each wire a weight. The pattern 00000101 is not just eight switches; it is a compact way to say five."
      tradeoff="Machines use fixed widths, so numbers can overflow or lose detail. The hardware only remembers as many bits as the design provides."
      next="Once bit patterns can mean numbers, logic gates can be arranged to transform those numbers."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-number" id="L4" data-title="Arithmetic">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">04</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Gates that add — arithmetic from logic</h2><div class="sub">numbers · the ripple-carry adder</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Addition is logic with memory of a carry, chained from bit to bit.</p>
    <Adder client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Arithmetic is logic arranged so carries move from bit to bit.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A stored number is inert until the machine can change it: add totals, compare values, advance counters, compute addresses."
      idea="Adder circuits use logic gates to combine two bits plus a carry. Chaining that tiny pattern across a word makes arithmetic happen in hardware."
      tradeoff="Simple adders wait for carries to ripple across the whole number. Faster designs spend more circuitry to shorten that wait."
      next="Now numbers can be transformed, so the same bit patterns can represent data, addresses, or instructions."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-meaning" id="L5" data-title="Numbers → things">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">05</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The same number, pretending to be many things</h2><div class="sub">meaning · encoding</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">The same byte can be a number, a letter, a color, or an instruction — meaning is an agreement.</p>
    <NumbersThings client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Meaning comes from interpretation; the same byte can be many things.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Hardware only stores bit patterns, but software needs those patterns to stand for text, colors, sound, files, and commands."
      idea="An encoding is a shared agreement: this number means the letter A, this triplet means a pixel color, this byte range means an instruction."
      tradeoff="Meaning lives in the reader. The same bits can become nonsense if decoded with the wrong convention or width."
      next="The CPU is the special agreement that treats selected numbers as actions to perform."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-meaning" id="L5b" data-title="Compilation / runtime">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">05.5</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Runtime: how code stops being text</h2><div class="sub">meaning · parsing · bytecode · machine code</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Your source code is for humans. Before the CPU can obey it, language tools have to turn that text into structured operations.</p>
    <RuntimePipeline />
    <Takeaway>A runtime is the bridge between human language and machine operations.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="The CPU cannot execute JavaScript, Ruby, Python, or C source text. It only follows lower-level operations."
      idea="Language tools parse the text, check structure, lower it into simpler steps, and either interpret, compile, or JIT those steps into CPU work."
      tradeoff="Runtimes buy portability and developer speed, but they add startup cost, memory overhead, optimization complexity, and sometimes pauses."
      next="After code becomes instructions or bytecode operations, the CPU loop has something concrete to fetch, decode, and execute."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L6" data-title="The CPU">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">06</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The CPU: a loop that obeys numbers</h2><div class="sub">systems · fetch · decode · execute</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">A CPU loops over numbers and treats each one as a command to fetch, decode, and execute.</p>
    <Cpu client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A CPU is a tiny loop that treats some numbers as instructions.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Without a CPU, every task would need its own custom circuit. We need one machine that can be reused by changing the instructions it reads."
      idea="The CPU repeats a small loop: fetch a number from memory, decode what it means, execute the operation, then move to the next instruction."
      tradeoff="General-purpose control is powerful but complicated. Registers, clocks, caches, pipelines, and interrupts exist to keep that loop useful and fast."
      next="Instructions need a place to live and data to work on, so memory becomes the machine's workspace."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L6b" data-title="Memory hierarchy">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">06.5</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Memory hierarchy: the CPU hates waiting</h2><div class="sub">systems · registers · cache · RAM · disk</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Memory is not one place. The machine keeps the hottest data closest to the CPU, then spills outward into slower, larger storage.</p>
    <MemoryHierarchy />
    <Takeaway>The memory hierarchy is a speed bargain: tiny and close is fast; huge and far away is slow.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="The CPU can execute instructions much faster than main memory or disk can feed it data."
      idea="Use layers of storage. Registers hold the current values, caches keep recent data nearby, RAM holds active programs, and disk keeps long-term state."
      tradeoff="The hierarchy is only fast when programs reuse nearby data. Random access, cache misses, and disk reads turn computation into waiting."
      next="Memory addresses now have performance meaning, which is why stacks, arrays, and locality matter."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L7" data-title="Memory">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">07</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Memory: numbers with addresses</h2><div class="sub">systems · arrays · the call stack</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Memory is bytes with addresses; the stack is where function calls pile up and unwind.</p>
    <CallStack client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Memory gives numbers addresses; the stack gives function calls a shape.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A CPU can execute instructions, but programs need somewhere to keep changing values, arrays, return addresses, and temporary state."
      idea="Memory gives every byte an address so code can say where to read and write. The call stack gives function calls a disciplined place to pause and resume."
      tradeoff="Memory feels huge, but distance matters. Cache misses, bad locality, allocation costs, and stack limits can dominate performance."
      next="Once many programs want CPU time and memory at once, the operating system becomes the referee."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L7b" data-title="Data structures">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">07.5</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Data structures: shapes made of addresses</h2><div class="sub">systems · arrays · hash maps · trees</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">A data structure is a promise about where data lives and how you will find it again.</p>
    <DataStructures />
    <Takeaway>Data structures are memory layouts plus rules for moving through them.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Raw memory is just numbered boxes. Programs need ways to find, group, order, and update related values without thinking about every byte."
      idea="Data structures impose shape: arrays put neighbors together, hash maps compute a bucket from a key, and trees connect nodes through choices."
      tradeoff="Every shape favors some operations and punishes others. Fast lookup, ordered traversal, easy insertion, and locality rarely all come for free."
      next="Once many programs use memory and structures at once, the OS has to isolate and coordinate them."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L8" data-title="Operating system">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">08</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The operating system: the referee</h2><div class="sub">systems · the scheduler · syscalls</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">The OS slices one machine into safe little turns so many programs can pretend they are running at once.</p>
    <Scheduler client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The OS makes one machine feel safely shared by many programs.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="If every app controlled the hardware directly, one bug could overwrite another program, freeze the machine, or steal private data."
      idea="The OS owns the hardware and rents out safe illusions: each program gets its own memory, files, devices, and turns on the CPU."
      tradeoff="Safety is not free. Isolation, scheduling, permissions, and system calls add overhead and make some operations more indirect."
      next="With one machine managed safely, the next problem is connecting many machines together."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L9" data-title="The network">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">09</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The network: numbers that leave the building</h2><div class="sub">systems · encapsulation · packets · TCP/IP</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">Network data travels as wrapped packets: addressed, routed, dropped, retried, and reassembled.</p>
    <Encapsulation client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Networking works by wrapping data with just enough context to survive the trip.</Takeaway>
    <p class="aside">Headers are overhead, but they buy routing, ordering, and reliability.</p>
    <Packets client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Packets can arrive late, lost, or out of order; protocols rebuild the original message.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Programs often need to talk across machines, but the path between them can drop packets, reorder data, or route through many strangers."
      idea="Network protocols wrap bytes with context: where they came from, where they are going, which program should receive them, and how to rebuild the stream."
      tradeoff="Reliability costs extra bytes and time. Headers, handshakes, retries, congestion control, and timeouts are the price of useful communication."
      next="When many networked machines coordinate to serve users, the stack becomes a cloud system."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-system" id="L10" data-title="The cloud">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">10</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The cloud: someone else's machines, at scale</h2><div class="sub">systems · load balancers · app servers · datastores</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">"The cloud" is the same machine repeated: load balancers, app servers, caches, databases, and queues.</p>
    <Cloud client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The cloud is the same stack repeated, coordinated, and scaled sideways.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="One machine is a single point of failure and a single bottleneck. Users may also be far away, making every request slower."
      idea="Cloud architecture repeats the stack across many machines: load balancers route, app servers compute, caches remember, databases persist, queues smooth bursts."
      tradeoff="More machines create new failure modes. Consistency, retries, observability, deployments, and cost become design problems, not details."
      next="A user action can now travel through browsers, networks, operating systems, memory, CPUs, gates, and voltage."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-physical" id="L11" data-title="…and back down">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">11</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>The lie, all the way down</h2><div class="sub">the whole picture</div></div></div>
    <p class="prose">A click becomes packets, processes, memory, arithmetic, gates, transistors, voltage — then climbs back up as pixels.</p>
    <p class="prose prose-follow">Every layer is a useful story told by the layer beneath it.</p>
    <Takeaway>Abstraction is the useful lie that lets humans build on top of physics.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="No one can hold electrons, gates, instructions, memory, networks, and distributed systems in their head at the same time."
      idea="Abstraction lets each layer present a simpler promise upward: a wire becomes a bit, bits become numbers, numbers become instructions, instructions become programs."
      tradeoff="The promise is useful, not perfect. Performance bugs, security issues, and outages happen when lower-layer details leak through."
      next="The final trace follows one piece of code as it crosses those promises."
    />
  </section>

  <section class="layer zone-all" id="L12" data-title="Trace a method">
    <div class="layer-head"><div class="layer-idx">★</div><div class="layer-titles"><h2>Watch it happen: one method, every layer</h2><div class="sub">the capstone · real algorithms, traced top to bottom</div></div></div>
    <div class="capstone-ribbon">all layers converge here</div>
    <p class="prose">Pick an algorithm and watch one line of code echo through the machine.</p>
    <Tracer client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A line of code is a story retold as VM ops, memory changes, arithmetic, and signals.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Source code feels like words on a screen, which makes the machine underneath easy to forget."
      idea="The trace ties one source line to the lower-level work it triggers: VM operations, data structures, memory movement, arithmetic, and systems effects."
      tradeoff="A trace is a lens, not the whole universe. It hides details so the important connections stay visible."
      next="Use it as the bridge back down the stack whenever software starts to feel magical again."
    />
  </section>
</Base>


<style>
  .zone-all{--accent:var(--blue)}
  .zone-all .layer-head{margin-bottom:14px}
  .capstone-ribbon{display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.16em;text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--blue);border:1px solid var(--border-hot);border-radius:999px;padding:6px 12px;background:var(--blue-d);margin-bottom:16px}
  .capstone-ribbon::before{content:"";width:7px;height:7px;border-radius:50%;background:var(--blue);box-shadow:0 0 12px var(--blue)}
</style>
